description.narrative: (Malawi): The southern region of Malawi is prone to droughts and floods. The frequencies and magnitudes of the droughts and floods affect food production leading to food insecurity, especially among the vulnerable households. Other factors such as environmental degradation, high population growth and lack of livelihood options exacerbates the food insecurity situation. The Food for Peace PL480 Pathways to Sustainable Food Security activity will improve food security and livelihoods for 63,472 direct beneficiary households in the flood and drought-prone Balaka and Machinga districts in Southern Malawi. USAID will use $788,700 of FY 2019 Title II resources, complemented with Community Development Funds to support activity interventions. FY 2019 illustrative interventions will include: 1) social behavior change around maternal and child health, water, sanitation and hygiene, nutrition behavior change and family planning using the Care Group Model; 2) the promotion of conservation agriculture, natural resource management, agribusiness, and informal micro-finance among smallholders; and 3) community-based disaster risk management. These interventions will improve maternal and child health, nutrition, and livelihoods among beneficiaries, and will increase the capacity of targeted households to withstand natural and economic shocks and stresses. The activity is aligned with the Integrated Country Strategy Mission Objective 2.1 to increase sustainable livelihoods and further aligned with the Feed the Future Strategy and Zones of Influence. The activity supports Goal 4.4 of the Joint Regional Strategy and Strategic Objective 2.2 of the Joint Strategic Plan..
